<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">Big surprise, I also agree with this argument.  Once something is "trivial" to you, you should be able to successfully make it while blindfolded.  (Perhaps that is why the comment no longer says "This item is trivial for you to make".)  Once you've hit the trivial level, success should be more like 90-95% than 50%.  I can see lower success for very low wisdom. (Wisdom's for how well you learn from your mistakes, after all.)  But as long as your wisdom is at least average, success should be all but automatic once you've reached the point where you can no longer improve your skill by making something.  For game mechanics to be otherwise discourages the development of trade skills.  As a result, players that might work on developing a skill will give up on it, and just stick to the one-dimensional camp out, hack and slash, get loot, type of game.  One would hope this is something Verant would prefer to avoid.</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
